ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the analysis of R2 and AIC values (Table 4), the adsorption of Ni(II), Cu(II), Cd(II), and Pb(II) ions onto β-CD(CA) and β-CD(CA)/QDs adsorbents follows the Langmuir–Freundlich isotherm model (Paul Guin et al., 2018). This isotherm model represents a high equilibrium condition for metal chelation and/or adsorptive processes driven by electrostatic attraction. According to this isotherm, the maximum theoretical adsorption capacities (q

                              m
                           ) of β-CD(CA)/QDs for Ni(II), Cu(II), Cd(II), and Pb(II) ions are 243, 229, 228, and 222 mg/g, respectively, while for β-CD(CA), the corresponding values are 213, 218, 207, and 201 mg/g, in the same order as mentioned earlier. These data suggest that under these experimental conditions, the maximum adsorption was achieved for Ni(II) and Cu(II) ions. It is worth noting that the adsorption of these metal ions varies depending on the nature of the adsorbent. The β-CD(CA)/QDs adsorbent exhibited a significantly higher adsorption capacity compared to β-CD(CA), demonstrating its potential not only as a fluorescence detector but also as a promising adsorbent for metal removal from aqueous media (Meng et al., 2023). To investigate the distribution of metal ions adsorbed on the surface of β-CD-based materials, EDX spectroscopy was performed. The obtained images, available in Fig. S7, reveal a quasi-homogeneous distribution of metal ions across the entire porous and irregular surface of the adsorbent. This suggests that the grooves and active sites of this adsorbent are uniformly distributed throughout its structure.
